  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The narrative surrounding the task force's work on integrating ORCID into books workflows demonstrates an emerging commitment to enhancing scholarly communications, even in the absence of traditional impact metrics such as citations or online mentions.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The task force, comprising authors including ORCID, Alice Meadows, and others, has engaged in crucial discussions regarding the incorporation of ORCID identifiers into book publishing workflows. This initiative is fundamental in streamlining author identification within the scholarly publishing landscape, fostering better recognition of intellectual contributions, and ultimately enhancing the integrity of academic records.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Despite the absence of specific impact indicators, such as citations or community discourse metrics, the work rests on a solid foundation of emerging methodologies that aim to address significant issues in scholarly communication. By focusing on ORCID's implementation in books, the task force highlights a pathway toward improved transparency in authorship and an enriched academic dialogue.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This article, hosted on Figshare, acts as a foundational output that can serve as a reference point for future developments in the intersection of ORCID and books. Recognizing the task force's efforts is vital as they provide insights into how such initiatives may facilitate broader acceptance and adaptation of ORCID across various publishing sectors, nudging the research ecosystem toward more inclusive practices.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">In this way, the task force's work contributes to ongoing developments in academic publishing, where traditional forms of impact may not fully capture the significance of initiatives addressing system-level changes. As the academic community continues to navigate the intricacies of authorship and recognition, this foundational work may become a cornerstone for future research that seeks to build upon this critical intersection.</p>",
